73:## Standing boundaries / invariants (guardrails, not next actions)
74:During any later propagation, PRESERVE the A004–A020 scope boundaries recorded in the accepted
75:resolutions (docs/67–113): each attack's improvement reuses existing objects and observability rather
76:than adding Core v0 entities; advanced analytics (collusion/network detection, ranking-bias dashboards,
77:actuarial calibration, participation-equity/delegation-network analytics, common-good charter mechanics,
78:beneficial-ownership registry) stay Extension v1+ / country implementation. The full per-attack invariant
79:list is in `docs/03_ROADMAP_HISTORY.md` ("Immediate next steps" #2–#17). A020 agenda-setting remains a
80:declared open problem gating open mode at scale.
81:
82:## Scope-control rule
83:Every new idea is classified as one of four types:
84:```text
85:A. Core v0                — necessary for the first coherent version of the model.
86:B. Extension v1+          — useful, but not required for the first model.
87:C. Country implementation — depends on legal/administrative/political choices of an implementing country.
88:D. Out of scope           — not necessary for the model and should not be solved now.
89:```
90:The project should not keep expanding unless a new idea is clearly Core v0 or a serious objection that
91:threatens the core model.
92:
93:## Operating rule
94:After every significant conversation or review round: (1) distill new concepts; (2) create/update
95:hypotheses/docs; (3) record objections; (4) update open questions; (5) classify new ideas by scope;
96:(6) communicate with the user in Spanish; (7) write durable repository documents in English; (8) include
97:concrete examples from the case under review; (9) revise the roadmap before every commit and whenever
98:the strategy changes.
