733:**Who do I complain to, and does it matter?** Complaints go into the
734:project's formal review path, not a suggestion box: they are traceable,
735:they must be reviewed, and if founded they can block payments, correct
736:scores, and mark responsibility. Sensitive complaints can be filed under
737:protected identity.
738:
739:**What if I have no time?** Your allocation then follows the public
740:default rule (which tracks published planning priorities), or a delegate
741:you chose. By design, inattention is a routed-for condition rather than a
742:failure mode: the default anchor absorbs the passive share. (In the
743:stylized simulation, a strong anchor buffered the *aggregate* loss when
744:active evaluation fell; within-cycle alignment still eroded, and the
745:symmetry gate does not establish resilience to participation decay — see
746:the caveat under "How this model has been tested".)
747:
748:**Who pays the independent inspectors?** Not the executor. Control work
749:is financed from a separated control budget attached to the project — a
750:distinct line citizens fund alongside execution — and inspectors are
751:assigned by protocol rule, so the money that pays verification never
752:passes through the hands being verified ([[40_CONTROL_SUBPROJECTS_AND_C002_RESOLUTION|docs/40_CONTROL_SUBPROJECTS_AND_C002_RESOLUTION.md]], [[52_FISCALIZATION_OFFER_COST_AND_C013_RESOLUTION|docs/52_FISCALIZATION_OFFER_COST_AND_C013_RESOLUTION.md]]).
